 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Project Neptune: Coastal Flood Prediction 🌊\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook is configured to run the Project Neptune data ingestion and model training pipeline directly on Kaggle. It leverages Kaggle's free GPU resources to accelerate the Graph Vision Transformer (FloodFormerGV).\n",
    "\n",
    "## 🛠️ Step 1: Uploading the Code\n",
    "1. You need to get the `Project Neptune` code into this notebook. You can do this by either:\n",
    "   - Uploading the `Project Neptune` folder as a **Kaggle Dataset** and adding it to this notebook.\n",
    "   - Or pushing your code to GitHub, and cloning it down in the cell below."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# If using GitHub, uncomment and run:\n",
    "# !git clone https://github.com/yourusername/project-neptune.git\n",
    "# %cd project-neptune\n",
    "\n",
    "# If using a Kaggle dataset, navigate to the dataset directory:\n",
    "# import os\n",
    "# os.chdir('/kaggle/input/project-neptune')\n",
    "# print(\"Working Directory:\", os.getcwd())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 🔑 Step 2: Configure API Keys\n",
    "Your pipeline requires access to the **Copernicus Climate Data Store (CDS)** to pull ERA5 data.\n",
    "\n",
    "To do this securely on Kaggle without exposing your key:\n",
    "1. Go to **Add-ons -> Secrets** in the top menu of your Kaggle notebook.\n",
    "2. Add a new secret called `CDS_URL` with value `https://cds.climate.copernicus.eu/api`\n",
    "3. Add a new secret called `CDS_KEY` with your actual token (e.g. `f1eef164-...`)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from kaggle_secrets import UserSecretsClient\n",
    "import os\n",
    "\n",
    "try:\n",
    "    user_secrets = UserSecretsClient()\n",
    "    cds_url = user_secrets.get_secret(\"CDS_URL\")\n",
    "    cds_key = user_secrets.get_secret(\"CDS_KEY\")\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Write the ~/.cdsapirc file required by the cdsapi library\n",
    "    rc_path = os.path.expanduser('~/.cdsapirc')\n",
    "    with open(rc_path, 'w') as f:\n",
    "        f.write(f\"url: {cds_url}\\nkey: {cds_key}\\n\")\n",
    "    print(\"✅ Copernicus Data Store credentials successfully injected.\")\n",
    "except Exception as e:\n",
    "    print(\"⚠️ Warning: Could not find Kaggle Secrets for CDS. Ensure they are set.\")\n",
    "    print(\"Exception:\", e)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 📦 Step 3: Install Dependencies\n",
    "We need to ensure Kaggle's environment has all the specialized graphing and climate libraries installed."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "!pip install -r requirements.txt\n",
    "\n",
    "# Ensure PyTorch Geometric and its specific compiled scatter/sparse dependencies are installed\n",
    "!pip install torch_geometric\n",
    "\n",
    "# PyG optional deep-learning extensions usually required depending on the CUDA version\n",
    "# Note: Kaggle notebooks typically run PyTorch 2.0+ with CUDA 11.8 or 12.1\n",
    "!pip install pyg_lib torch_scatter torch_sparse torch_cluster torch_spline_conv -f https://data.pyg.org/whl/torch-2.0.0+cu118.html"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 🚀 Step 4: Run the Pipeline\n",
    "Execute the main pipeline! This will first trigger the ERA5 and NOAA datasets to download (which may take hours for large areas), process them into a training Zarr structure, and finally initialize your Deep Learning Training Loop.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Tip**: Ensure your `config.yaml` is using small subset blocks for your first test run to ensure everything connects properly before doing a full 5-year run!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "!python flood_prediction/main.py"
   ]
  }
